Based on Elmore Leonard's character, \"Justified\" has been a pleasant surprise over its four seasons. Marshall Rayland Givens was sent back to Harlan county--his old backyard--the one place he didn't want to go after a shooting that occurred during the first season. The first three seasons focused on the conflict between Rayland, a former friend turned enemy Boyd Crowder, Mafia associate Wynn Duffy. Season four sets up an entirely new series of plot twists.SPOILERS:The fourth season of \"Justified\" starts off with a thud. Drew Thompson fell from a plane sometime during the 1980's having stolen a large stash of cocaine and money. Maybe Drew didn't die though and one of the few people who might know is marshal Rayland Givens' (Timothy Olyphant) father. Everyone is converging on Harlan hoping to either discover if Drew is alive and hiding out in Harlan county or, at the very least, how to recover the money and drugs he disappeared with including Rayland's friend/nemesis Boyd Crowder (Walton Goggins).END OF SPOILERS:One of the best written, directed and acted shows currently on TV, \"Justified\" continues to have a fascinating series of twists and turns that befits a show adapted from a novel and stories by the late Elmore Leonard. The 13 episodes are involving and this blu-ray (and the DVD set) has a strong series of special features as well.The Blu-ray transfer for the fourth season of \"Justified\" looks exceptionally good with a sharp, detailed transfer with colors that pop.The 5.1 audio mix sounds terrific as well with a nice spread among the surround speakers and considerable activity.The special features include the following: we get 10 commentary tracks (I haven't listened to all of them yet but what I have heard so far are pretty good commentary tracks); \"Deadly Series: Constantable Bob\" a good profile for a new character this season played by comedian/actor Patton Oswald; deleted scenes and outtakes; \"Becoming Boyd\" that puts the spotlight on the marvelous character actor Walton Goggins; \"Anatomy of an Episode\" a self explanatory featurette; a script to scren comparison on the finale and, finally, the featurette \"The Veterans' Experience\".\"Justified\" has managed to continue to expand beyond the limited scope of the conflict between Rayland and Boyd while still retaining both characters involving a terrific storyline for the fourth season.Highly recommended"
