SyFy is turning into pretty much of a bad joke these days, Continuum is one of their better offerings and worth a look.I watched Season 1 last January/March and am currently watching the DVD set to refresh my memory before tonight's Season 2 premiere. Only 10 episodes and at $22.96 not as cheap as I'd like it to be but still an interesting idea with a cop from 2077 inadvertently finding herself in 2012 Vancouver British Columbia searching for escaped terrorists from her time.Some criticize the &#34;tech&#34;, I think a lot of it either already exists or is under consideration/development, the time travel device being the exception. My biggest complaint is the anti business tone taken by the plot line, I doubt that- with the worlds' governments collapsing, that the corporations would survive to take over and run things.Lot's of plot mysteries introduced, hopefully to be explained as the series goes along. I want to know who supplied Liber8 with the time device and just what's going on with Kiera Cameron and young/old Alec Sadler- hopefully I'll get to find out.Give Continuum a try, not a bad &#34;cop story&#34; even if you don't like science fiction.."
I enjoy this show, but I don't love it. I love looking at Rachel, and I love the fact that it's about time travel, but I still wait for interesting plots that actually have an effect on time. I think I am also waiting for Kiera to reveal to her partner that she's from 77 years in the future. I'm so relieved there is a Season Two, so the plot line can develop more. So far it's been average, but since it is about time travel, I have to stick with it."
I am looking forward to seeing where they take all of this.  Meanwhile, it's always fun to watch Rachel Nichols work :)"
Continuum is a time travel story and dystopia, that like all dystopias examines problems in our current society. The main character is a detective in a future where the corporations are the government, the bankers, the social service agencies and the arbiters of everything. As in all societies, some people live better than others and our detective is one of those. She doesn't question the reasons for the violence of the terrorists, but works on catching them and executing them. During their execution, our detective and all of the terrorists are sent back in time to our own era. Our intrepid heroine manages to find friends and a place in the local police force that allows her to survive and for single arc episodes. I do wish though that writers could come up with a framework for weekly episodes other than the detective solving cases. That said, Continuum has a lot of potential.The fact that we enter the story on the side of the satisfied and blind citizen of the corporatocracy rather than with with the revolutionaries fighting injustice is an interesting place to enter the narrative from a conceptual point of view. Normally, we would be with the freedom fighters - instead, we are with one of the \"lucky\" citizens of the dystopia who has a good job and life and family and can live without the freedoms she is denied because she isn't denied as many of them. The freedom fighters are fighting in the right cause, but killing innocents, how many times has idealism led to terrible bloodshed in the history of the world? How many of us ignore injustice as long as we have our comforts and can ignore the exploitation and suffering of others? Continuum has the potential to be morally complex as long as the writers don't blink.In summary, the detective framework is getting more than cliched but Continuum has a lot of moral complexity to it. I hope the writers continue to explore this and give us greater depth in terms of the revolutionary characters and our detective. How does she react to a society that is on the road to her society, but is more free? Does she start to see the problems of the future? How do idealists fighting for human freedom justify and live with the murders of innocents? I can't believe that not one of our fighters isn't having PTSD or moral quandaries about this. I would love to see these issues explored, with or without the case of the week. I will keep watching Continuum, which might turn into a great show."
I really kinda like this show & Rachel Nichols is very good as a cop accidentally sent back from the future along with some major bad criminals. She has just the right mixture of being hot & sexy & yet being a girl that can really kick butt."
I watched the first episode and kept waiting for the good guys, i.e. ordinary citizens fighting a world taken over by corporations, to win. It quickly became clear that ordinary people were the BAD GUYS in a world run for and by corporations. I guess if they produce enough of these, impressionable children will think that is a good thing. Adults not so much. They own the media I won't add my hard earned entertainment dollar to support this propaganda."
