While watching original programming move from the big networks to AMC, SyFy, FX, etc. I have been pleased with the inversion of quality from cable shows being the B shows with poor writing and low budgets to watching them take over what quality is still out there while the major networks flounder.  Continuum is a show that like many of SyFy's newest generation of shows leverages some lesser known names, though quite good performers, and the improved funding and writing to produce quality shows.  SyFy naturally appeals to those who enjoy the Science Fiction Genre, but are introducing both comedy and some real world situations into their stories.  Continuum is a show that caught me and hooked me very quickly as the whole time travel paradox is not ignored while the story lines develop using real life social/political situations as the basis for both the chosen image of the future as well as the events of modern day corporate, political, and social landscape to influence the writing to include some very real subjects that are presenting themselves as large corporations and technological advances shape our society and government goals and structure.  Nobody gets into office without major financial backing which controls the policies they support (not campaign speak, actual actions).  The show does a great job of being entertaining as it introduces the very real potential for ever increasing influence of the corporate world over the political.  If the 2007 bailout didn't drive home the point, the government policies of not enforcing anti-trust have allowed financial institutions to become so large that their failure would destroy the world economy.  If that isn't influence I don't know what is.  But Continuum does a great job of being a good science fiction show predicated on a future in which the government is the corporations (hardly a stretch), debt is the master of the ordinary citizen (again, hardly a stretch) and then the biggest part of the storyline, time travelers from the future coming back to modern day times to try and change that future from coming to be.  The first season does a great job of using the episode stories with their regular flashbacks to the future to establish the characters roles and quickly blur the lines between the good guys and bad guys.  While our main character only begins her learning journey the first season does a good job of quickly establishing the basis for the longer term story while being remaining with each show being  entertaining.  I'm biased haven seen season 2, but I so far see a series that started great and has just gotten better.  I hope it is on for years to come and the writing continues to expand the scope of the importance of what these characters are doing and choosing and turns black and white to many shades of grey making it interesting and causing the viewer to question some very deep seeded assumptions.  It is the thinly veiled ties to what we find in the papers daily that makes this show so intriguing and make me hope future seasons can build on that aspect and possibly get funding for more than 13 episodes a season (the one MAJOR drawback to modern day shows)."
Good acting, thought provoking storylines - but - - start thinking, are the terrorists really the bad guys, is the cop from the future having doubts and seeing the merit behind the terrorists goals, but not their means? Who are really the goodies and the baddies? You need to think deep to start realizing that all is not as it appears, but the potential is intriguing!"
So I was really looking forward to this show. I looks like hard sci-fi. Which I love. It's got two actresses whom I like. Lexa Doig (Andromeda) and Jennifer Spence (SGU). X-file's \"smoking man\" is in it. And it is Canadian SYFY (I love Sanctuary & Lost Girl). So this seemed like a shoe in. Ugh! 1)65 years is not enough time for corporations to take over the world and impose a police state. I mean, that's just lame. 2) 65 years is not enough time for us to have all that great tech. Biometrically calibrated suits? Transformer guns? Come'on! 165 years...maybe. But barely 6 centuries?. No, I don't think so.3) How is the Kiera's husband not a terrorist when he totally over react to her being stationed in the execution room. )Even though I know it was old Alex's doing. 4) All the ethnic people are bad. 5) One more, all the ethnic people are bad. 7) Let me say that again. There are only 2 black dudes and 2 asians... all bad. 8) The \"bad guys\" are the anti corporation Liber8 (lame name!) and the \"good guys\" are corporations?! Really? Is this show funded by BP? 9) Alex, the wunderkin, runs a sky net style lab in his shady (Those folks look all kinds of suspect!) parents barn?! I could go on. This show just wasn't my cup of tea. The science is lack luster and while the tech seems cool it is is just not believable. I will give this one more chance only because I love SYFY but it better get good real quick because I simply don't have the emotional stamina to watch a whole show that promises to be awesome science fiction and delivers nothing but badly thought out she-ite. I'm looking at you Lost."
