TAKEN 2 (Dir. Olivier Megaton, and I'm not kidding, 2012, 93 minutes) was fun for me to watch, tough to review because it's a mindless \"actioner\" serving only to showcase Liam Neeson's immensely likeable talents. That man can go from playing Oskar Schindler to performing better than Steven Seagal ever did, as he does here.Neeson returns as CIA security field agent Bryan Mills, this time convincing his ex-wife and daughter to accompany him to Istanbul. They refuse at first - that is only wise - yet in Istanbul suddenly, there they are! Surprise, dad!! What kind of evil international hoodlums are you going to kill for us this time?! In this case, it is the crazy father of one of the men Neeson killed in the original 2008 film.So of course the film spirals down from that point. As I said, the director makes this a fun film. The cinematography is not bad, making Neeson look exactly like a killing machine yet his own skills add to that crisp editing. The man fights better than Seagal on film, and sadly the editing gets too crisp with some of his fight scenes merely a hint and not shown. Too many car chases in Istanbul ... how I hate car chases. These have no style to them, but at least they're over rapidly.The film has a snappy, rapid-fire approach to the violence and its only real redeeming quality is Neeson. It is rushed, illogical, nearly brainless: a typical popcorn film and I enjoyed it as such. It has nowhere near the stunning panache or the skill of the originalTaken(see my review).As it is, it seems both films were virtually ignored. In fact, the originalTaken, a remake of Steven Seagal'sBelly of the Beast, convinced me that they should have made Neeson the next James Bond and Spielberg ought to have kept him on to playLincoln.This has the talents of returning stars Jon Gries (another great perennial favorite of mine though he's a bit of a ghost in this two-second-role), Famke Janssen and Maggie Grace.As for the rest, it's take-it-or-leave-it 'international violence'. But I love nearly anything Neeson does, and I certainly enjoyed this dumb, all-action \"CIA family\" film with its Goth soundtrack - done so brilliantly in the original film - and its careful shadings of color, light and darkness.It's a lot of work for what ended up appearing to be a direct-to-video mediocrity!"
