The fourth season of Justified may be a little weaker than in past seasons, but it is still very good.  The main theme of this season was trying to track down a drug smuggler that faked his death years ago and then assimilated into Harlan County.  Both the Marshals and the Bad guys end up looking for him, which of course pits Raylan and Boyd with each other and against each other as in past seasons.  Of course there were ancillary plots going along the way that all ended up intertwining.There were new characters introduced along the way, most notably Colton played by Ron Eldard and Bob played by Patton Oswald.  Natalie Zea had a much reduced role this season (likely because of her role on The Following). and Limehouse returns toward the end of the season.  Unlike the first couple seasons there is far less of a &#34;bad guy of the week&#34; formula to the show.  They pretty much stick to the story arcs, so you cannot just jump in and know what is going on.  There is still the blend of action, drama and dark comedy that, along with the wonderful acting, has made the show so great.  There was probably less interaction between Raylan and Boyd this year (especially when just the two of them were involved), but when there was Timothy Olyphant and Walton Goggins continue to have great chemistry.  The main storyline does get resolved by the end of the season, but they also set up a lot for season 5 including consequences for Eva becoming more and more bad.For those who get the discs themselves, there are commentary tracks on some of the episodes, a few behind the scenes features with the actors and showrunners,  Not a ton of material, but what is there will make those who like the extras happy.  If you have liked the previous seasons you will likely enjoy this one as well."
