SaB is a favorite series at our house, even though we're outside of the target demographic (15 - 22ish).  I love learning about deaf culture and even a bit of ASL as the story progresses!"
I watch this series out of cultural fascination for the mix of so many elements:  hearing, non-hearing, ASL, lip-reading, lack of communication, incorrect perceptions, defensiveness, compassion.  Allowing the sign to be sub-titled with no affect of speech interjected or voice over is unique, refreshing and challenging for a non-ASL viewer.  This element, deafness, is what takes this series beyond the normal, Disneyish teen drama.  There is all of the angst and plot contrivances with one parent's infidelities as well as the competition and jealousies of peer groups in schools.  But, being a hearing person versus being a non-hearing person reveals an entirely new component:  the desperation on both sides to be understood, the clannish pride, self-protective, of the deaf, the impatience and mockery, at times, of deaf students versus hearing students, teenagers still going through all the yuck of teendom.  There is this giant educational component in this series, but it is absorbed by the normalcy of parents, teens, upper class and working class life that lifts this series to a different realm.  Well worth watching."
